Today I heard the retelling of a myth: ✨An infant born under inauspicious stars was destined for a painful, difficult life. It’s parents had no resources to offset this prediction; they left the child in a temple hoping the gods would give it a better life. Hard times did befall the child but they grew into a wise and peaceful teacher with no trace of bitterness. People asked, “what is the secret to changing your fortune? How did you turn your destiny around?” The child, now teacher, replied: “I learned who I truly am, not who others presume me to be. I released the ego-made self and embraced the true self underneath.” ✨

This is a very paraphrased version of the tale but the phrase ‘ego-made self’ is original, and one I resonate with again and again. I had many positive, incredible experiences in 2022 but at times I still felt protective, withdrawn, and self-conscious of how others perceived me. But really, it was how I perceived myself. 

The ego projects a distorted view of our true selves; when we release the self-made ego we can appreciate the real qualities that make up who we are as individuals. We, you, have the power to determine our/your own Self.

🖤 2022: I am grateful for the wonder and joy, the sadness and doubt. These experiences made me more certain of what I want. I release them!

❤️ 2023: I will continue to heal, open up, dive into new experiences knowing I will either succeed or fail - and that either is perfectly okay. I accept my ego and understand it is part of me but not all of me.

Thanks for following along on this journey. Wishing everyone reflection, intention, and good vibes 💛💛 Happy New Year!

Papadarius 14a - my fourth of the grade and what felt like second hardest after Zulu. I had to finagle some truly short-person / small-box beta shenanigans throughout this climb, particularly the red point crux shown here. Couldn’t do the iron-cross span so I iron-rosed instead 🥀 Felt myself start to lose steam at the top… the inner voice saying, “you’re too pumped, you’re going to fall” and starting to imagine myself falling but I stared daggers at the next hold, threw for it, and drowned out the doubt with a try-hard scream. Sharp focus won out in the end 🗡️ 

I was so fcking frustrated with my (what felt like) slow progress on Papadarius but some things can’t be rushed. I never regressed; I learned a little bit every time. I did what I could in the moment and let everything else - things I couldn’t control - fade away. Relatively, Papa didn’t take me a super long time but it did feel emotionally drawn out.

Psyched to finish Papa in the midst of training for my upcoming Rumney trip. Shoutout to my belay team @tchenrock @madaleinesorkin @tiny_brit_tiny @neodude Andrew, Def, and everyone at the River Wall cheering me on. Proud of us for braving the heinous winds this season!! 😂

Thank U, Next 😌😉

One dry day, three total climbing days, and nine days overall into this Rumney trip - a classically New England spring season. I’m a little frustrated of course but also nostalgically appreciative; weather is a big part of Rumney’s local character. Rain, humidity, seepage, unpredictability… you need strategy and patience to climb here. A great learning environment 🌧️😜 

The stoke is high though! On the one dry day I reached my high point from last season and made a decent overlapping link. I’ve been stuffing towels in the cracks, refining beta, and hanging with family in the meantime. Even got a few cheeky rides in despite the flood warnings 🤩🚲 

This weekend and next week’s forecast is looking promising. Stoked for dry rock and fun times with @jordi.llauvi 🎥 and @tchenrock @interdymensionall 🙌🏼 

@thenorthface @thenorthface_climb @scarpana @organicclimbing @gnarlynutrition @blackdiamond

China Beach 14b ✨✅✨ Teenage Neenz is freaking out. I first tried these moves back when I was a team kid for RIRG (now @rockspotclimbing); I clipped the chains two days ago and can still hardly believe it. I remember getting so stoked watching Dosage II hometown heroes @dave_graham_ @joekinder @lukeparady raging in Rumney and putting New England on the map. The stoke gets stronger every time I come back, alongside a deep appreciation for what it means to climb on the East Coast. The conditions demand patience, dedication, a willingness to try hard no matter what, and logistical timing to get things done. I’ve re-learned all those lessons and more.

China Beach feels like the most personally meaningful ascent of my career thus far, largely due to my emotional attachment to the East. I’m psyched to be the first woman / shortest person 😜 up the ‘Big Kids Wall’ and so very thankful for everyone who helped this childhood dream come true. On this trip alone, @jordi.llauvi for capturing the moment 🎥 @tchenrock @interdymensionall @gilroyscott for belays, moral support, and celebration Oreos. @dana_seaton my forever-coach. @rajivayyangar @chinabeachpodcast forever stoked. @conwayjason @brock_climber @joshlevin94 @grahamowens1 @tchenrock @interdymensionall for all the micro-beta. Ward Smith for bolting. @dave_graham_ for the FA. Mom & Dad ❤️ 

Big thanks to @thenorthface @thenorthface_climb for supporting this trip. Stay tuned for a full video from @jordi.llauvi!! 

#climbing #sportclimbing #rumney #rumneyrocks

I started trying handstands in December 2022. Pretty stoked on this progress 😊 Yoga and cycling have helped my climbing motivation immensely. Keeps me flexible too 😁

Here’s what I’ve learned as a handstand gumby:
1) stretch your wrists/shoulders.
2) make an L-shape with your body, face towards the wall. Lift one leg and slowly try lifting the other. 
2) ask for/be open to feedback.
3) practice! 

Not pictured in this reel: many more failed attempts, small fits of rage, rubbing my wrists because I didn’t stretch them, and watching how-to TikTok videos. 

Also important: while the first shot was my early attempt and the last shot my most recent, my progress was not linear as this reel may suggest! Some days I’m on point and others I can barely get my feet off the ground. But I love playing 🥰 and if I’m not feelin handstands, I try something else. 

Whatever your goals are, keep at them! 🙌🏼

Okay so Steck-Salathe is absolutely wild and I’m now convinced it should be a mandatory route for all Valley climbers, mostly because the thought of doing this BITD in basically hiking boots is nuts and we should all consider that as we’re struggle-squeezing through the Narrows. 

Big thanks to @nicolamartinezz for telling me which direction to face in the slots, and the gentle encouragement juxtaposing my swearing. 

This experience made possible by @americanalpine & @unitedinyosemite 💛 more on that later. For now, just grateful for these wall bruises.

@thenorthface_climb @scarpana @organicclimbing #climbing #yosemite

@unitedinyosemite - a gathering of climbers in pursuit of easier access to this magical Valley 🧡

It’s pretty hard to stay and climb in Yosemite if you’ve never been, don’t know your way around, and aren’t familiar with the community. Historically marginalized groups experience these difficulties even more.  @unitedinyosemite changed that by organizing food, camping, and mentorship within climbing and land stewardship practices. I was honored to teach a bouldering clinic with @urban_ndn_ and hang with folks in the evening as part of the inaugural event!

This visit was also special because the @americanalpine Club gathered in Yosemite for our summer board meeting. I’m incredibly lucky to work with a group of people so dedicated to change within our community! There is good work being done and I’m excited to focus my energy as board VP into the AAC’s continuing growth. 

Big thanks to the @unitedinyosemite organizers for bringing us together, and a particular thanks to @scarpana for helping me get out there. Till next time Yosemite ❤️ 

#climbing #unitedinyosemite #americanalpineclub

@psicocomp 2023 - the wall got taller but we still did it 🤩 Found myself in the same position from 10 years ago: second pixelated photo in 2013 sitting atop that glorious, god-forsaken ledge 55ft off the deck, contemplating my life choices. Third photo same wall but 60ft (65ft??) on a floating barge above Lake Michigan. Staring across the city skyline, I couldn’t help but smile big. What an absolutely ridiculous, amazing place to be. I’ll always be scared up there and I’ll always be grateful for such an incredible, unique experience. 

In addition to competing I also premiered my China Beach film, spoke on @thenorthface’s Climbing & Culture panel, got interviewed by local news, explained DWS to curious soon-to-be-climbers, gave my sunglasses to a TikTok montage, made sure everyone who wanted one had a tequila shot, and had an all-around blast. Quite the full-value time!! Thank you @thenorthface_climb @chris_sharma and @psicocomp organizers for bringing this event back in full force 💛

Here’s to another year of dreaming big ✨💭✨ and big love to the folks in my life who dream with me 💛

Exhausted; I had completed the longest 🚲ride of my life and I wasn’t even half way done with the day, We still had to hike, climb the 💎 , and summit Longs before reversing the whole thing (and by the way, the phrase uphill both ways is actually a thing).

Last year I got a text from @sheneenagins ”want to climb the diamond?”. The next day I surprised her with a late start, 8 cams, 3 micros, and a rope slightly thicker than floss. On the approach, I learned that it was her first time on route, but somehow I knew we would be ok, as we descended, we talked about goals. Somewhere in my distant future, The Longs Peak triathlon was on my list. Little did I know how soon that "some point" would arrive.

No records were set, but we completed our original sub-24 hour goal, and made it to our board meeting the next day! I probably should’ve trained a little bit more, but we finished. And so thankful that I basically could draft the whole way — well besides the shortest and most fun part — the actually rock climbing.

Now on to the next thing — anyone looking to buy a bike???

Just a few 😮‍💨 of my falls off the crux of Wacka Flocka. This stab move is low-percentage and the couple moves after are still hard. My first visit to China left some big impressions. I’m Chinese on my mom’s side. Walking around Shanghai (where my grandmother was born) and climbing in Lijiang were equal parts a culture shock and a homecoming at the same time. Being around so many Chinese people, seeing Chinese athletes on the walls at @thenorthface offices, hearing Mandarin and Cantonese and so many different Asian dialects around me, feeling a sense of belonging even though I am still very much a bumbling American foreigner. I felt joy. I felt grief. I wish my Nen Nen and Yea Yea were still here… There’s a lot we don’t know about our family history, their stories. I’m sad about that and also happy that I get a chance to create my own story with China. 

Incredibly grateful to @thenorthface @thenorthface_climb for making this trip happen. It was really fun traveling around with @nathaniel.coleman. Big thanks to Rex, Jonny, @andrea_chao_ @yuediaries @theclinic.international and all the climbers who shared their stoke with us. I am still processing this trip while already planning my return visit. 

Xie xie! 🥹

Front Range home vibes ✨ in my routine. 

6 weeks ago, before leaving for China, I injured something in my palm - localized, acute soreness directly under the middle finger. The pain would come after (not during) a climbing session but it got worse over the course of my travels to the point of near-constant aching. After making it through the Dual Ascent comp I cut my trip short and returned to the States. 

For the last two weeks my hand rehab has been TBlock hangs and a couple 60min easy bouldering sessions. I’ve also been getting a solid nights sleep, drinking a ton of water, reading morning/eve, shooting my daily ginger juice (lol), and eating more consistently. Also cycling, doing yoga/mobility, and hanging with friends 💛 

I think these habits, as important as the finger rehab itself, has contributed immensely to a faster healing process. The ache still hurts but is slightly less. I wanted to push it a little and was so bold as to try a short session on the 🌙 board - with success! Felt a little scary punching for moves but I chose problems with straightforward holds/beta. The ache afterwards was not much different than other times.

I haven’t gotten an official exam from a physio since the pain seems to be improving. Am listening to my body and caring for it in other ways 🤗

Now for a little trip to New England for some family time! Then back on the program 💪🏼

@thenorthface_climb
@scarpana 
#climbing #recovery

Got some requests for my ginger juice recipe so here ya go! Start for the health benefits and stay for the burn 😈🔥 I take a shot every morning. This is false causality but I haven’t gotten sick for the last year 😉 just sayin. 

Don’t overthink the recipe. It’s ginger, lemons, and water; roughly one lemon per 5-6oz of ginger. You don’t have to peel the ginger if you strain with a nut bag. Add whatever else you like (turmeric, honey, cayenne, etc) but the key is making the process easy enough to take on a regular basis. Consistency builds health ☺️ 

Enjoy! 🍋🫚💛

Picking up memories from 2023 and asking, does this one bring me joy? If it does not, I thank it and leave it gently behind. The ones that do I carry with me into 2024. 

Last year started with heartbreak that forced me to give a long, hard look at my self. The ensuing months were filled with big emotions and a scrambling sensation of arranging puzzle pieces with no reference picture. I climbed hard, biked far, travelled the world and had some hilariously unhinged experiences with new people while deepening friendships with those already so dear to me. 

I’m still filling in the puzzle. These are some pieces I’m bringing into 2024. Thankful for my friends and family for making last year’s memories so bright 💛 Let’s make this year a work of art! 🌄
